# ============================================================================
# IMPORTANT NOTES FOR STUDENTS
# ============================================================================
#
# 1. Why use .gitignore?
#    - Keeps repository clean and small
#    - Protects sensitive information
#    - Prevents committing generated files
#    - Makes collaboration easier
#
# 2. What to commit:
#    - Source code (.py, .js, .jsx)
#    - Configuration files (package.json, requirements.txt)
#    - Documentation (README.md, guides)
#    - Small static assets (images, icons)
#
# 3. What NOT to commit:
#    - API keys and secrets (.env)
#    - Dependencies (node_modules, venv)
#    - Build outputs (build/, dist/)
#    - Large files (models, datasets)
#    - System files (.DS_Store, Thumbs.db)
#
# 4. Checking ignored files:
#    - See all ignored files: git status --ignored
#    - Check if file is ignored: git check-ignore -v filename
#
# 5. Accidentally committed sensitive data?
#    - Remove from history: git filter-branch or BFG Repo-Cleaner
#    - Change the exposed secrets immediately!
#
# ============================================================================
